00:43:47,641 --> 00:43:52,441
Being self-sufficient is not, is a great thing for the Greeks.

489
00:43:52,440 --> 00:43:54,121
I mean, Agamemnon was self-sufficient.

490
00:43:54,641 --> 00:43:56,961
All heroes are self-sufficient.

491
00:43:56,961 --> 00:44:03,921
And generally, the only alternative to being self-sufficient is to be slavishly dependent on somebody or something.

492
00:44:03,920 --> 00:44:06,880
But, of course, from a Christian point of view, we talked about that.

493
00:44:06,880 --> 00:44:09,760
Being self-sufficient is a very, very bad thing.

494
00:44:09,760 --> 00:44:37,520
Pride is the thing that we are the people at the bottom of the inferno in Dante who are self-sufficient, who are so detached and cold-blooded that they're literally frozen in ice, and who, and I mentioned this, I think, but I'll mention it again because of the third man, the bottom people are so self-sufficient that they're ready to betray anybody just for their self, just to be self-sufficient.

495
00:44:37,521 --> 00:44:38,800
That's Harry Lyme.

496
00:44:38,800 --> 00:44:41,201
Those are the worst things.

497
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:49,601
Our people are the totally selfish and totally self-sufficient and thereby betraying type of people.

498
00:44:49,601 --> 00:44:54,881
Yvonne's got a big betrayal problem going on later in the book.

499
00:45:01,920 --> 00:45:03,441
Oh, yeah, okay.

500
00:45:03,760 --> 00:45:23,441
So now we will see what happens in Zosima's cell, where everybody is revealing that Justin is very clever to have this family meltdown take place in Zosima's cell, where everybody tells you right off in front of everybody else what they are really up to.

501
00:45:23,440 --> 00:45:26,081
And that's a good way to get started.

502
00:45:26,081 --> 00:45:30,720
And so everybody's confessing, and everybody's going crazy.

503
00:45:31,681 --> 00:45:34,001
And guess what?

504
00:45:34,880 --> 00:45:38,921
Alyasha is totally involved and upset.

505
00:45:38,920 --> 00:45:44,440
And Yvonne is watching this like a spectator, as if he was going to, you know, he could give a story to the newspaper.

506
00:45:38,481 --> 00:45:45,880
Oh, he's not going to do that with this one.

507
00:45:46,201 --> 00:45:51,401
At the bottom of 51, Alyasha stood with hanging head on the verge of tears.

508
00:45:51,400 --> 00:46:09,881
What seemed to him strangest of all was that his brother Yvonne, on whom alone he had rested his hopes and who alone had such influence on his father that he could have stopped him, sat quite unmoved with downcast eyes, apparently waiting with interest to see how it would end, as though he had nothing to do with it.

509
00:46:11,001 --> 00:46:18,121
That really sums up this observer stance of Yvonne.

510
00:46:20,041 --> 00:46:37,001
And Dostoevsky, as a Christian, but a very special sort of Christian, is very, very down on this sort of detached self-sufficiency in which someone doesn't feel involved with other human beings and the world at all.

511
00:46:37,001 --> 00:46:42,840
Ivan is just too good for this world, and that's not a position to want.

512
00:46:42,840 --> 00:46:46,681
That turns out not to be a good position to be in, as you can imagine.

513
00:46:46,681 --> 00:46:48,840
But Dostoevsky has to show you.

514
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:50,121
He can't just tell you.

515
00:46:50,121 --> 00:46:55,481
And it takes a while until we see how badly things go for him.

516
00:46:55,481 --> 00:46:56,841
But let's go on.

517
00:46:57,481 --> 00:47:00,121
So he's an intellectual.

518
00:47:00,440 --> 00:47:02,681
He's the only brother that goes to the university.

519
00:47:02,681 --> 00:47:04,600
Alyasha went to the monastery.

520
00:47:04,601 --> 00:47:06,441
Dimitri goes to the army.

521
00:47:06,440 --> 00:47:08,041
Everybody goes where they belong.

